Profitability: Profitability remained mixed over the period. Field-level gross margin (revenues less production expense) declined by 989 bps to 56.0% in FY25 from 65.9% in FY24, as revenues declined 25.0% to $359.3m from $479.0m while production expense declined only 3.3% to $158.2m from $163.5m, reflecting the fixed cost-heavy nature of the Company's offshore and multi-country asset base. Operating margin deteriorated by 3,423 bps to (5.7%) from 28.5%, with operating income of $136.5m in FY24 swinging to an operating loss of ($20.6m) in FY25, primarily driven by a $67.2m non-cash impairment charge on Canadian assets classified as held for sale, lower revenue across all geographies, and a 11.5% increase in G&A to $33.1m from $29.7m, partially offset by a 23.1% reduction in DD&A to $110.0m from $143.0m. Excluding the non-cash impairment, operating margin would have been 13.0%, a contraction of 1,552 bps versus FY24. Net income swung to a loss of ($41.4m) from net income of $58.5m, a deterioration of $99.9m or 170.8% YoY, driven primarily by the $67.2m impairment, lower realized pricing with average realized price declining 15.0% to $56.11 per BOE from $65.64 per BOE, and the absence of the $13.5m bargain purchase gain recognized in FY24 from the Baobab acquisition, partially offset by income tax expense declining to $14.8m from $81.3m. Adjusted EBITDAX was $173.4m in FY25, reflecting the Company's strong underlying cash generation despite the headline GAAP loss.
